  v_resume_a CLOB := q'|Although rhyme, as a refrain of identical sounds, belongs only to modern poetry, this study of stylistic metrics aims to demonstrate that Greek and Latin poets have a range of specific verbal patterns at the verse-end. This allows to establish a hierarchy of clausulae, varying according to epochs, literary genres, scenes, in two of the most frequent verses of the ancient drama, namely iambic trimeter and the senarius. It is a veritable repertory of the poet can draw on. From Archilochus to Phaedrus, from Athens to Rome, this study goes through the many stages of this evolution, focusing on commonalities and divergences of the two poetic traditions, Greek and Latin.|';
